# Function to create QQ plots for model variables against the response
def qq_plots(data, predictors, response):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=len(predictors), figsize=(20, 4))
    
    for i, predictor in enumerate(predictors):
        # Calculate theoretical quantiles and sample quantiles
        model_fitted_y = data[predictor]
        model_residuals = data[response] - model_fitted_y
        
        (osm, osr), (slope, intercept, r) = stats.probplot(model_residuals, dist="norm", plot=None)
        axs[i].plot(osm, osr, 'o', label=predictor)
        axs[i].plot(osm, slope*osm + intercept, 'r-', label=f'Q-Q line')
        axs[i].set_title(f'Q-Q Plot for {predictor}')
        axs[i].set_xlabel('Theoretical Quantiles')
        axs[i].set_ylabel('Ordered Values')
        axs[i].legend()

    plt.show()

# List of predictors
predictors = ['LivingCost', 'CI2p0c', 'PPAA', 'Unemployment','GenderDiversityRank'] 

# Perform QQ plot analysis
qq_plots(train_data, predictors, 'MedianIncome22')

In [15]:
# Feature Engineering Steps
# 1. Aggregate RGDP
train_data['AverageRGDP'] = train_data[['RGDP19', 'RGDP20', 'RGDP21', 'RGDP22']].mean(axis=1)

train_data['AveragePopulation'] = train_data[['P20','P21','P22']].mean(axis=1)

# 2. Interaction Between Living Cost and an average CIipjc metric (demonstration purposes only)
# Assuming 'CI1p0c', 'CI1p1c' ... 'CI2p4c' represent different CIipjc metrics
ciipjc_columns = [col for col in train_data.columns if 'CI' in col and 'c' in col]
train_data['AverageCIipjc'] = train_data[ciipjc_columns].mean(axis=1)
train_data['LivingCost_CIipjc_Interaction'] = train_data['LivingCost'] / train_data['AverageCIipjc']

# 3. Economic and Demographic Ratios
train_data['GDPPerCapita'] = train_data['AverageRGDP'] / train_data['AveragePopulation']

# Display the first few rows to verify the new features

In [20]:
# Including both numerical and categorical transformations in the preprocessor
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numeric_transformer, numeric_features),
        ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
    ])

# Re-creating the pipeline with the correct preprocessor
reg = Pipeline(steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor),
                      ('regressor', LinearRegression())])

# Training the model with the corrected setup
reg.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predicting on validation set again
y_pred = reg.predict(X_val)

# Evaluating the model again
rmse = mean_squared_error(y_val, y_pred, squared=False)

Performing Cross Validation¶

In [21]:
# Custom scorer for RMSE as it's not directly available in sklearn
rmse_scorer = make_scorer(lambda y_true, y_pred: mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred, squared=False), greater_is_better=False)

# Perform 10-fold cross-validation and evaluate both RMSE and R2 metrics
scores = cross_validate(reg, X, y, cv=10, scoring={'RMSE': rmse_scorer, 'R2': 'r2'}, return_train_score=False)
average_rmse = -scores['test_RMSE'].mean()

# Function to create QQ plots for model variables against the response
def qq_plots(data, predictors, response):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=len(predictors), figsize=(20, 4))
    
    for i, predictor in enumerate(predictors):

        model_residuals = data[response] - model_fitted_y

        axs[i].plot(osm, osr, 'o', label=predictor)
        axs[i].plot(osm, slope*osm + intercept, 'r-', label=f'Q-Q line')
        axs[i].set_title(f'Q-Q Plot for {predictor}')
        axs[i].set_xlabel('Theoretical Quantiles')
        axs[i].set_ylabel('Ordered Values')
        axs[i].legend()

    plt.show()
